@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(vii) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it names a `def` (`double`) WITHOUT calling it, to bind it as a
-- first-class function value. eval has this for free — a top-level `def` is a VFn in
-- the environment, so `let f = double` captures it — but the compute spine emits each
-- `def` as a JS `function` statement, not a value: a bare def name is an out-of-scope
-- `Var`, which the lowerer refuses as a free variable. The differential harness must
-- report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier — never a
-- miscompile, never a JS crash.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values
-- — a `fn x -> …` bound, captured, passed, returned, and called through a local name
-- (see compile_closure_test). The frontier now sits at FIRST-CLASS `def` REFERENCES —
-- naming a `def` as a value rather than calling it. This file binds one, so it still
-- refuses; when def references lower (a later D1 slice), it flips from `unsupported`
-- to a print with no edit.

def double(n: Number): Number
  n * 2

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let f = double
  println(f(5))
